Authentication – Who is making the request?
In EKS, the identity is verified using AWS IAM.

Authorization – What is that user allowed to do?
This is controlled using RBAC.

Creating IAM Users
I’ve added them with the AdministratorAccess policy just for the sake of demo.
Each user has their own access key ID and secret, which is configured using AWS CLI on my system

aws configure
aws sts get-caller-identity  #to get info of which user 

AWS-AUTH
Updating aws-auth ConfigMap
For mapping AWS IAM users to Kubernetes clusters, We have to use aws-auth ConfigMap.
==> kubectl -n kube-system get cm aws-auth -o yaml

==> kubectl -n kube-system get cm aws-auth -o yaml > aws-auth.yaml
 So export this aws-auth configmap to a file

AWS-AUTH  FOR USER
==> cat aws-auth.yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: aws-auth
  namespace: kube-system
data:
  mapRoles: |
    - rolearn: arn:aws:iam::650781539051:role/eksctl-my-eks-1703aaa-nodegroup-my-NodeInstanceRole-jMat4ycG93uB
      username: system:node:{{EC2PrivateDNSName}}
      groups:
        - system:bootstrappers
        - system:nodes
  mapUsers: |
    - userarn: arn:aws:iam::650781539051:user/bharath
      username: bharath

AWS-AUTH  FOR

apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: aws-auth
  namespace: kube-system
data:
  mapRoles: |
    - rolearn: arn:aws:iam::650781539051:role/eksctl-my-eks-1703aaa-nodegroup-my-NodeInstanceRole-jMat4ycG93uB
      username: system:node:{{EC2PrivateDNSName}}
      groups:
        - system:bootstrappers
        - system:nodes
  mapUsers: |
    - groups:
      - my-read
      userarn: arn:aws:iam::650781539051:user/bharath
      username: bharath
    - groups:
      - my-read
      userarn: arn:aws:iam::650781539051:user/bharath
      username: bharath-01

ROLE
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: Role
metadata:
  namespace: dev
  name: role-dev-read
rules:
- apiGroups: [""]
  resources: ["pods","services","configmaps"]
  verbs: ["get", "watch", "list"]

ROLE BINDING FOR USER

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: rolebinding-dev-read
  namespace: dev
subjects:
- kind: User      #Group
  name: bharath   #my-read
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: Role
  name: role-dev-read
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io


ROLE BINDING FOR GROUPS

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: rolebinding-dev-read-group
  namespace: dev
subjects:
- kind: Group
  name: my-read
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: Role
  name: role-dev-read
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io




✅ What you should do
1. In aws-auth ConfigMap
You can define any group name (even if it doesn’t exist in IAM):
                               
mapUsers: |
  - userarn: arn:aws:iam::123456789012:user/teju
    username: teju
    groups:
      - dev-group
  
  - userarn: arn:aws:iam::123456789012:user/teju
    username: teju-01
    groups:
      - dev-group                             

✔ dev-group → just a name (no need in IAM)

2. In RoleBinding
Use the same group:
                               
subjects:
- kind: Group
  name: dev-group
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io




